shire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1168–1213":"circa 1168–1213","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1172–Female":"1172–Overleden","1194–Male":"1194–Overleden","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","about 1194":"circa 1194","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1213":"1213","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1200":"circa 1200","about 1168":"circa 1168","about 1210":"circa 1210","ABT 1193":"circa 1193","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Islip, Oxfordshire, England":"Islip, Oxfordshire, England","of,Oxfordshire,England":"Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1168–1213":"about 1168–1213","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","1194–Male":"1194–Deceased","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","about 1194":"about 1194","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1213":"1213","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1200":"about 1200","about 1168":"about 1168","about 1210":"about 1210","ABT 1193":"about 1193","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Islip, Oxfordshire, England":"Islip, Oxfordshire, England","of,Oxfordshire,England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Courcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"iV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert iV de Courcy was born about 1168, in Islip, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Guillaume de Courcy I, was 33 and his mother, Isabelle de l'Aigle, was 29. He married Mathilde de Houdetot about 1193, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1213, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1168–1213":"umbes 1168–1213","1168–1213":"1168–1213","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1194–Male":"1194–Surnud","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1136–1176":"1136–1176","1140–1187":"1140–1187","about 1194":"umbes 1194","1176":"1176","1187":"1187","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1213":"1213","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1168":"umbes 1168","about 1210":"umbes 1210","ABT 1193":"umbes 1193","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England"